ift-2-inch-spacer-lift-kit-for-ford-transit-awd-2wd-1.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182735/quigley-qlift-2-inch-spacer-lift-kit-for-ford-transit-awd-2wd-1.jpg 1297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182735/quigley-qlift-2-inch-spacer-lift-kit-for-ford-transit-awd-2wd-1-297x110.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182735/quigley-qlift-2-inch-spacer-lift-kit-for-ford-transit-awd-2wd-1-800x296.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182735/quigley-qlift-2-inch-spacer-lift-kit-for-ford-transit-awd-2wd-1-120x44.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182735/quigley-qlift-2-inch-spacer-lift-kit-for-ford-transit-awd-2wd-1-768x284.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182735/quigley-qlift-2-inch-spacer-lift-kit-for-ford-transit-awd-2wd-1-696x258.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182735/quigley-qlift-2-inch-spacer-lift-kit-for-ford-transit-awd-2wd-1-1068x395.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182735/quigley-qlift-2-inch-spacer-lift-kit-for-ford-transit-awd-2wd-1-1135x420.jpg 1135w\"></a></p><p>Transit AWD kit pricing is $3,495 for vans without a rear factory sway bar, and $3,745 if it comes with a rear sway bar…and those prices are if you bring your van to Quigley for the service. Throw in a Bilstein shock upgrade at the same time for another $900.</p><p>Prices may vary if you have someone else install it based on that party’s labor rates, but they’ll only sell it to an authorized installer. Currently, that includes <a href=\"http://vandoit.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">VanDOit</a>, <a href=\"https://fieldvan.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Field Van</a>, and <a href=\"https://www.newbergford.com/van-headquarters\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Newberg Ford</a>.</p><p>The 2WD kit will be a little bit less, but not dramatically so. Labor and parts will be fewer, but they don’t have final pricing for that as of this story going live.</p><figure id=\"attachment_269132\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-269132\"><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit.jpg\" alt=\"vandoit camper van with quigley q lift kit\" width=\"720\" height=\"343\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit.jpg 720w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit-297x141.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit-120x57.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit-696x332.jpg 696w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb28 src ng ngcb28 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit.jpg 720w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit-297x141.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit-120x57.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23182751/vandoit-ford-transit-with-quigley-qlift-2-inch-lift-kit-696x332.jpg 696w\"></a><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-269132\">Not my van.</figcaption></figure><p>As a current VanDOit (RWD only) van owner with oversized offroad tires, I can tell you right now the 2″ lift is worth it if only to prevent the front tires from rubbing the bump-stops on every. single. little. bump.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.quigley4x4.com/products/qlift/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Quigley4x4.com</em></a></p></div></div>","author":"Tyler Benedict","siteTitle":"Bikerumor","siteHash":"49f427af0a926f4232eb837006841d7242e153e3afbb590f32e4b104ea3e2718","entryHash":"3c1d20ef7ea66650dcaada08b46311a067ead8042e1b55793381aee7a69ae9d4","category":"Cycling"}